Introduction

This document describes the longitudinal modeling of assisted reproductive technology utilisation (ART) as a function of the United Nations produced Human Development Index (HDI) and Gender Inequality Index (GII). Greater details on the rationale for the study can be found in the main manuscript.

Summary of methods and findings:

  • Linear mixed effect model for log ART over time with covariates GII and HDI
  • GII only available for year XXX so data restricted to these years.
  • GII related to log ART, increased GII related to increased ART utilisation. Effect marginally significant.

Data

There is more detailed description of the data used in the following files:

  • …

Several countries are removed from the analysis due to poor data quality (or missing data in the case of Taiwan)

Index models

We create two linear mixed effect models for log ART utilisation. Both include random intercept terms for country and time, the HDI and GII as variables. The second model differs in decomposing the variable effects into within country and between country effects. The rationale for this was to assess whether there was evidence that increases in GII within a country over the timeframe of our dataset were associated with increased ART utilisation.

We note the following:

  • The GII is only available for the years: XXX,
  • Several countries are missing outcome data for some of the relevant year.
  • Time is years, centered so that 0 is XXXX.
  • The GII and HDI are between 0 and 1.

Decomposition formulation

This model decompose effects effects into within country and between country effects. effects. The resulting between and within coefficients can be compared to assess whether it is reasonable to assume that the between and within country effects are similar, which can be used to reason about causation of the effect etc. We originally decomposed time as it is measured unevenly between countries (due to missing outcome data) and this is recommended in the literature, however it results in non-identifiability.

In general the previous model is a better fit, with better model fit statistics and a hypothesis test that the between and within effects of GII are equivalent being non-significant.

Standard formulation - L2 shrinkage on fixed effects

In order to deal with the collinearity we apply \(L2\) shrinkage to the fixed effects (as is already done to the random effects). We scale the data so the covariates are zero mean and standard deviation one. We also mean centre the outcome to remove the need for an intercept term.

Firstly, we refit the unpenalised model to the scaled data.

Appendix A: additional models

Standard formulation with excluded countries

A better model with the excluded countries included adds a Middle East/North Africa indicator variable. Note that due to the high variability of (within country) ART rates in the excluded countries these results may not be reliable.

Model: log ART utilisation = time in years + GII + HDI + Middle East/North Africa + random country intercept
